post_text:
Thank you to everyone who has donated in honor of Elaine Lamski, beloved HPS teacher for 29 years. An amazing $10,500 has been donated, to date, to the memorial fund to support Elaine’s dream to give students opportunities to experience their foreign language curriculum first-hand.
Elaine‘s book, “The Book of Elaine,” is also available on Amazon. Elaine’s family & co-author, Amy Peirce are generously donating all proceeds to the memorial fund.
A special thank you to Elaine‘s husband, Dale and sons, Todd and Aaron, for continuing to support Elaine‘s love of her HPS kids.
If you would like to donate to the fund, you can do so through our community give day:
https://www.givehastings.org
Choose Hastings Public Schools Foundation, and in the “note about donation” section put “ELAINE.”
￼￼￼

post_text:
The HPS Foundation is supporting the efforts of the Jonathon Reiber Memorial Soccer Festival Board who is raising money for soccer score boards on the HHS soccer fields. Jonathon Reiber was killed by a drunk driver in 1999, shortly after graduating from HHS, and his friend and teammate, Jason Marr took up the cause to stop drunk driving by organizing an annual “free-to-play” soccer tournament held annually for the past 18 years where students could hear the message about not drinking and driving while enjoying a great day of soccer. The Jonathon Reiber Memorial Soccer Festival organization has given out 93 scholarships for a total of $78,250 during the 18 years of the tournament.

We need to raise $15,000 by June 1st for the soccer scoreboards. You can get more information on the Jonathon Reiber Memorial Soccer Festival and donate at
https://www.reiberfestival.com/donate

Checks may be made out to “Jonathon Reiber Memorial Soccer Festival” and can be mailed to treasurer, Larissa Knudsen, 13909 Pine St Omaha NE 68144

Put "Matching" in the Description area on the payment checkout page.

Take a look at these lovely young people from the Class of 1941. Thanks to the granddaughter of Dorothy Corwin, the Hastings Public Schools Foundation is pleased to display a number of senior photographs from the Class of 1941. Do you know any of these “young” people?

*Just a reminder that the Hastings Public Schools Foundation is here to help your HHS graduating class prepare for reunions, whatever your year of graduation! Contact us with your reunion dates and times. We can answer questions about how to go about setting up a reunion and make local arrangements. post_text: Great night to be a Tiger!!
shared_text:
Hastings High Booster Club added 35 new photos to the album: Athletic Hall of Fame Banquet.
September 27, 2015 at 12:43 PM ·

Thank you to everyone who attended our inaugural Athletic Hall of Fame Banquet last night. I think everyone had a great time seeing friends, teammates, and people that they admired and were inspired by in the years they attending Hastings High.

Congratulations to all of the Inductees, and their families who accepted their awards. Wonderful speeches were given by each individual, teammate, or one of their family members. It was nice to hear their stories, relive their glory moments, and to hear the excitement and admiration in their voice.

Thank you to Athletic Director Tracy Douglas, and her committee for organizing this wonderful event. Also thank you to those who donated items for the silent auction, and the corporate sponsors.

We are all looking forward to next year's Athletic Hall of Fame Banquet. GO TIGERS!

The Hastings Public Schools Foundation awarded 46 scholarships to 2015 HPS graduates for a total of $52,052 this spring. The HPSF Board of Directors and Staff wish to thank those of you who have helped to provide the scholarships that will help these students find the PATHWAYS TO THEIR HOPES AND DREAMS.

Staff Idea Grants are one of the most effective means of encouraging innovative upgrading of classroom materials and technology and promotion of staff development that is beyond the
resources of the Hastings Public Schools. For the 2015-16 school year, the Hastings Public Schools Foundation will expend $10,020 for Grants that will impact eighteen teachers and their classrooms. These particular grants are made possible through donations from the Hastings Philanthropic Yoga Society, Hastings Public Schools employees, and matching funds from the Kinman Oldfield Family Trust.

When you give to the Hastings Public Schools Foundation, you really do give a gift that keeps on giving.

http://bit.ly/1IloNqG

Thank you to all of those who donated during the second annual Give Hastings Day! The Hastings Public Schools Foundation raised the third highest amount of money, with $13,275 being donated in this 24-hour online giving event. These donations, from you our generous donors, will make such a great difference in the lives of children in the Hastings Public Schools!

As a community, the goal was to raise $300,000 for the 69 non-profits involved and the day ended with just over $336,000 being raised! If you didn't get the opportunity that day to participate, you can still do so throughout the year! Our donation page, as well as the pages of all of the other organizations will be live and you can see updates of the great things that these organizations are doing for the people and community of Hastings.

post_text:
Give Hastings Day is only 1 day, 9 hours, and 28 minutes away from right now! The Hastings Public Schools Foundation is participating in this 24-hour online fundraising event created to rally community support for local charitable causes. This unique one-day fundraiser will be held on Friday, May 1st, 2015, from midnight to midnight. You can donate online during those hours or drop a check off to the Hastings Community Foundation (located in the Heritage Bank Building) at 800 W. 3rd Street, Suite 232 from 8-8 that day.

We hope you will consider supporting the HPS Foundation where your money will go to future Foundation projects like a High Ability Student Enrichment Program, a Writing Lab at Hastings High, Professional Development Programs, Foreign Language Programs at the elementary level, and a Pre-School Program. Visit our donation page today to learn more and then visit again on Friday to donate! Every donation counts and helps a great deal! Any amount from $10 on up is accepted!

It's all about the KIDS! With your help we can do better! YOU can make a difference.

post_text: Claren Kerr II, a 1977 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Thursday, December 11, 2014. He graduated from the University of Missouri in 1981. He married Beverly Phillips in December 1986. Claren was co-manager of Kerr Apple Orchard, Inc. in Lexington, Missouri, from 1987 until 2003. He and Beverly then lived in Peachtree City, Georgia. He was employed by the Transportation Security Administration at the Atlanta International Airport at the time of his death. Claren always had a smile on his face and a twinkle in his eye for his family.

post_text: Jeremy James Thompson, a 1995 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Wednesday, December 3, 2014 after his battle with cancer. Jeremy was born June 5, 1976 in Arlington, Texas. He resided in Fairbury Nebraska until he moved to Hastings in 1981. After graduation, Jeremy worked at Wal-Mart for several years. He enjoyed spending time with his family, the family dogs, watching sports and cooking shows. He also enjoyed listening to music and going fishing.

post_text: Barbara Jean Dyer Stickels Beck, a 1950 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Friday, November 21, 2014. Barbara married Charles E. Stickels on January 9, 1953. She and her family were confirmed in Saint Mark’s Episcopal Pro-Cathedral in 1964. In 2006, she married William Beck with great joy after reuniting with him in 2004 at their 50th Hastings College reunion. She enjoyed travel especially through Europe, reading, playing bridge, history, and entertaining. She was well known for her love of an active social life. Barbara was a member of Mary Lanning Volunteers, American Red Cross, 4-H Leader, Lochland Country Club, Saint Mark’s vestry and PEO Chapter G.

post_text: Michael Hull, a 2011 HHS graduate and senior at Hastings College, will perform a trumpet recital this Sunday, November 2, 2014 at 7:30 p.m. in Perkins Auditorium in Fuhr Hall of Music on the Hastings College Campus. Michael is pursuing a Bachelor of Music degree in Trumpet Performance and Music Education. He is the son of Jerry and Renae Hull, of Hastings. The performance will include selections composed by Giuseppe Torelli, Johann Hummel, Otto Ketting, Eugene Bozza, and Herbert Clarke. The performance is free and open to the public. AND...congratulations goes out to Michael for being named a recipient for the NMEA Student Teacher Grant!

post_text:
HPS FOUNDATION WINDS, PERCUSSION, AND STRINGS FOR KIDS

Our goal is to provide string and band instruments for HPS students who want to play, but cannot afford to.

There are three ways an individual or business can contribute to the HPS Foundation Instrument Donation Program:

1. DONATE a new or used instrument to the Hastings Public Schools Foundation.

2. MONETARY DONATIONS can be made to the Hastings Public Schools Foundation specifically for instrument purchase.

3. SPONSOR A STUDENT as an individual or a business by renting or purchasing a new or used instrument for one or more students through the Hastings Public Schools Foundation.

To donate, make check payable to:
HPS Foundation (memo line should specify HPS Instrument Donation Program) Send check to; HPS Foundation, 1924 West A Street, Hastings, NE 68901

You will receive a tax deductible receipt and, upon request, can be recognized in concert programs for in-kind donations or monetary support.

Hastings Public Schools
September 8, 2014 at 10:39 AM ·

"The student body and staff had a big surprise for me at the end of the day on Friday. I was blindfolded and led outside to a waiting convertible (at that point I was a little leery). When the blindfold was removed there was a huge parade of students and staff lined up around the school blowing horns and waving signs. How 800 students kept that a secret is a miracle in itself! I hadn't heard one thing about it! Some of the signs were really funny like 'Essink for President' and 'Please come back'. It was truly inspiring and I want everyone to know how much it was appreciated and that you all have a great bunch of kids!" - David Essink, HMS Principal

post_text: Leland Nordstrom, a 1965 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Friday, August 1, 2014. After graduation, Lee attended and graduated from Milford Technical School. He worked for 35 years in construction in Omaha for E & K Drywall and Allied Construction. Lee loved life. He loved to hunt and fish with his lifelong friend Mike Keeler and had a trailer in Niobrara for 40 years. Lee hunted for geese in Mexico, Canada and Brazil, wild boar in Texas, caribou and big horned sheep in Alaska and antelope in Wyoming. He loved to fish in Montana and South Carolina. Lee's home resembled a taxidermy shop full of mounts. Lee was proud to be a member of Ducks Unlimited and the Safari Club and he often went on hunts with these groups.

post_text: Dean R. Mosier, a 1968 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Wednesday, July 23, 2014. Dean went on to attend Hastings College and University of Nebraska at Lincoln. Following college, Dean worked at Kohtz Sales in Hastings and then at Mosier Construction as co-owner with his father for many years. He had been employed the last twenty-six years at Adams County Roads Department. Dean married Alyce Stocks on September 1, 1973, and to this union, a son, Thomas, was born in 1983. Together they enjoyed golf, gourmet club and camping. Dean liked to hunt, fish and be outdoors. He enjoyed time with family and friends. He was the past Grand Chancellor of Knights of Pythias.

post_text: Steven D. Spilinek, a 1972 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Thursday, July 24, 2014 after a long and courageous battle with cancer. He entered the U.S. Army and served from September 29, 1973, until July 16, 1975. He graduated from Central Nebraska Technical College. After graduation he worked as an electrician at several local businesses. He worked for Hastings Utilities for the past 33 years. He really loved his job and especially the people he worked with. He always said they were like a family to him. Steve worked up until a few days before his passing. Steve was united in marriage to Julie Zaroban on April 7, 1979, in Hastings. To this union three sons, Bradley, Tyson and Justin, were born. Steve coached his sons’ soccer, baseball, and softball teams. He was a soccer referee for many years. Hastings Community Theater played a big role in his life. He also enjoyed Husker football, the College World Series, the World Cup, and attending theatrical productions across Nebraska. He was a member of the Hastings Masonic Lodge #50 serving as Master Mason in 2003.

We just wanted to alert you to this in case you know Meghan Schuff Zimmeran from the HHS class of 2003 or so you could help a fellow alum in need.

Meghan is fighting Cystic Fibrosis, a disease she was diagnosed with at the age of 6 months. Cystic Fibrosis is a terminal illness that attacks a person’s lungs, sinuses, and digestive tract. Although there is hope for the future, there is currently no cure for CF. Meghan is now in need of a life-saving double lung transplant and the Children's Organ Transplant Association has started a fundraising effort to aid Meghan. Checkout the site below to learn more.

Meghan's mom, Cheryl Schuff, is a first grade teacher at Lincoln, Elementary School in Hastings.

post_text: Charlene Lingelbach Rutt, a 1952 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Saturday, April 26, 2014. She was employed by the Department of Labor as an interviewer until her retirement in 1996. Charlene was a member of First St. Paul's Lutheran Church, PEO, National Association of Retired State Employees, charter board member of Hastings Literacy Council, Altrusa International, was past president of PTA at Morton Elementary School and an honorary life member, and taught Sunday School and Confirmation classes as well as being very active and volunteering at church.

post_text:
Dr. Jim and Lynn Kaiser will be retiring from Hastings Public Schools this spring and we want to bid them farewell in a musical way! We hope you will join us on Thursday, May 8th at 7:45 p.m. at Hastings Middle School (201 N. Marian Road) or come at 7 and enjoy a great music concert from our 7th & 8th graders beforehand! A recognition for the Kaisers will take place immediately following the concert, around 8 p.m.

Jim has been with HPS for 42 years and Lynn for 26 years. We want to show them how grateful we are for all they have done for the HPS music program and for music in the community of Hastings! If you want to participate in a musical way, send us a private message through here or email Rick Matticks rmatticks@esu9.org to learn more. We want to keep some of this a surprise from the Kaisers, so we will refrain from posting all of the fantastic details on here See you May 8th!

post_text: Margaret Harpham, a 1966 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Tuesday, April 15, 2014. She worked as a Mental Health Security Specialist at the Hastings Regional Center Bridge Program and retired in 2010. She also had worked at the Kenesaw Corner for several years. She enjoyed crocheting, raising flowers, computer games and Facebook.

post_text: Shelly Will Van Meter, a 1979 graduate of Hastings High School passed away peacefully on March 10th in the presence of her family, after a two-year fight with cancer. She spent many years in the United States Army as an operating room technician attaining the rank of Sergeant before being discharged. After her time in the Army, she attended the University of Louisville and graduated in 1995 with a Bachelor of Science degree in nursing. She worked many years in surgery and also served as the director of nursing for the Hastings Correctional Center before its closing. She adored spending time with her family, especially her son Zachary. Shelly loved animals, especially her dogs, and was an avid supporter of Start Over Rover in Hastings.

post_text:
Richard 'Dick' Spady, a 1947 graduate of Hastings High School, passed away Friday, February 28, 2014. He attended the University of Nebraska-Lincoln and played minor league baseball for the Dodgers each Spring and Summer. Dick completed his master's degree in Agricultural Economics and Farm Management in May of 1958 and then married Norma Wolf on June 14, 1958.

Dick then served as an employee of the Nebraska Game and Parks Commission in various capacities ranging from land manager to assistant director. In 1974 they moved to Hastings where he became a partner at McKinley and Lanning, a farm management and farm loan firm. Dick was a caring husband and loving father and grandfather. During his lifetime he touched many others though his generosity and leadership.
